# Multiple contiguous opening brackets/braces/parens share a single
# level of indent rather than each adding one. When the user writes
# `[{...}, {...}]` with the first `{` contiguous with `[` (no newline
# between), the struct's own Nest already provides one level of
# indent; the list should not stack another on top. Contiguous
# opening/closing also means `[{` and `}]` stay adjacent even when
# content inside the structs breaks — the inner Group is free to
# break, but the list's brackets never inject a newline at those
# boundaries. Consequently no trailing comma is added when `]` hugs
# the last `}`.
-- in.cue --
x: [{
		a: _
	},
	{
		a: _
	}]
-- out/relpos --
x: [{
	a: _
},
{
	a: _
}]
-- out/norelpos --
x: [{a: _}, {a: _}]
